      <title>Iran restricts internet access amid gasoline protests</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANIran started restricting access to the internet on Friday, November 15, with nearly all access to the internet being restricted by Saturday, November 16, according to a report from NetBlocks, an organization that monitors worldwide internet access.The organization says Iran now only has five percent of ordinary levels of connectivity to the internet. This comes amid protests against the government's plan to hike gasoline prices.The Iranian government plans to increase prices for rationed gasoline by 50 percent, the New York Times reports. Those who purchase gasoline that exceeds the ration limit will face a 300 percent increase in fuel prices.According to the NetBlocks report, some of Iran's largest mobile network operators including MCI, RIghtel and IranCell, all fell silent around 6:00 p.m. on Saturday.Authorities must work with internet service providers and mobile data providers to shut down all internet connections, reports Wired.Alp Toker, director of NetBlocks, told Wired these telecoms would also need to overcome protections in a network system which are meant to make the system resilient in case of accidental outages or bugs. Toker noted that Iran's initial internet slowdowns may have been due to these very protections in the leadup to the now almost complete internet shutdown.The clampdown on internet service is believed to be designed to limit the number of people attending protests and to hinder media coverage, according to NetBlocks. Apps such as WhatsApp and Instagram have also been blocked.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Laptop with its internet connection being restricted2. Three Iranian mobile network operators falling silent around the same time3. How Iranian authorities could have worked to shut down all internet connections4. Why Iran is restricting access to the internetVOICEOVER (in English): "Iran started restricting access to the internet on Friday, November 15, with nearly all access to the internet being restricted by Saturday, November 16, according to a report from NetBlocks, an organization that monitors worldwide internet access."The organization says Iran now only has five percent of ordinary levels of connectivity to the internet.""This comes amid protests against the government's plan to hike gasoline prices." "According to the NetBlocks report, some of Iran's largest mobile network operators including MCI, RIghtel and IranCell, all fell silent around 6:00 p.m. on Saturday.""Wired reports that authorities must work with internet service providers and mobile data providers to shut down all internet connections.""Alp Toker, director of NetBlocks, told Wired these telecoms would also need to overcome protections in a network system which are meant to make the system resilient in case of accidental outages or bugs.""Toker noted that Iran's initial internet slowdowns may have been due to these very protections in the leadup to the now almost complete internet shutdown.""According to NetBlocks, the clampdown on internet service is believed to be designed to limit the number of people attending protests and to hinder media coverage.""Apps such as WhatsApp and Instagram have also been blocked."SOURCES: TechCrunch, NetBlocks, Wired, New York Times, Associated Press https://techcrunch.com/2019/11/17/iran-shuts-down-countrys-internet-in-the-wake-of-fuel-protests/https://netblocks.org/reports/internet-disrupted-in-iran-amid-fuel-protests-in-multiple-cities-pA25L18bhttps://www.wired.com/story/iran-internet-shutoff/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/17/world/middleeast/iran-protest-rouhani.htmlhttps://apnews.com/2062e5a7e6b3447d9af1b42141661f01***]]></description>
