      <title>Hong Kong pro-democracy candidates win big in local elections</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANHong Kong held its local district council elections on Sunday after almost six months of anti-government protests.Voter turnout was more than 71 percent, up from 47 percent in 2015, BBC News reports. The elections are considered to be a test for the current Hong Kong government.The city has a total of 18 district councils, of which the pro-democracy camp won 17, according to the South China Morning Post. District councils mainly advise the government on local issues concerning their district, such as the use of public facilities and public services.Several prominent pro-democracy activists including Jimmy Sham, who was attacked by masked assailants with hammers last month in Kowloon, managed to win district council seats in the local elections.The district councils may play a significant role when electing Hong Kong's chief executive in 2022.This is because the city's leader is elected by a 1,200-member committee, which includes 117 members chosen by district councillors. In this system, whichever campclaims the majority of votes, has the ability to claim all 117 of these seats.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Hong Kong local election turnout2. Pro-democracy parties won 17 out of the 18 district councils3. How these elections could influence the votes for the city's chief executive4. How these elections could be tied into gaining seats in the Legislative CouncilVOICEOVER (in English): "Hong Kong held its local district council elections on Sunday after almost six months of anti-government protests.""BBC News reports voter turnout was more than 71 percent, up from 47 percent in 2015.""The elections are considered to be a test for the current Hong Kong government.""The city has a total of 18 district councils, of which the pro-democracy camp won 17, according to the South China Morning Post.""District councils mainly advise the government on local issues concerning their district, such as the use of public facilities and public services.""The district councils may play a significant role when electing Hong Kong's chief executive in 2022.""This is because the city's leader is elected by a 1,200-member committee, which includes 117 members chosen by district councillors. In this system, whichever campclaims the majority of votes, has the ability to claim all 117 of these seats.""This could influence who is chosen to be the city's chief executive as the pro-democracy camp already held roughly 400 committee seats before the district council elections.""As six out of 70 seats are reserved in the city's Legislative Council for district councillors, the pro-democracy camp may also secure seats in the Legislative Council as the majority.""Hong Kong's Legislative Council has the ability to enact, amend, repeal laws or even start an impeachment process against the city's leader."SOURCES: BBC News, South China Morning Post, Hong Kong Free Press, Euronews, Reutershttps://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-50531408https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3039151/hong-kong-elections-tsunami-disaffection-washes-over-cityhttps://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/11/23/hong-kong-holds-protest-election-will-produce-protest-result/https://www.euronews.com/2019/11/24/hong-kong-elections-four-keys-to-understanding-district-council-pollshttps://www.reuters.com/article/us-hongkong-protests/hong-kong-democrats-score-landslide-victory-in-local-elections-amid-political-crisis-idUSKBN1XY0MZ?il=0***]]></description>
