      <title>Excess body weight can weaken efficacy of flu vaccine</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANScientists have found that the flu vaccine is less effective for people with excess weight.A study from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill found that vaccinated obese adults have twice the risk of flu or flu-like illnesses compared to vaccinated healthy-weight adults.NPR reports that during the 2009 flu outbreak, health experts noticed the infection was worse in individuals who were significantly overweight.The virus grows to higher concentrations and spreads deeper in the lungs.Heavier individuals were also more likely to spread the disease.A University of Maryland study found that more of the virus came out of the exhaled breath of those who were overweight or obese.According to Chapel Hill nutrition professor Melinda Beck, the metabolic shift in people's bodies caused by gaining excess weight affects immune system cells.So although obese people may still make an antibody response, their T-cells aren't functioning, so they can still be infected with the flu despite being vaccinated.Apart from the obese and overweight, elderly people also face the same problem.Because of this, scientists are now working to develop a next-generation flu shot that can address these vulnerabilities, though it has years to go before it's ready.In the meantime, they say people should still continue to get vaccinated, regardless of size or body weight.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Flu vaccine less effective in overweight, obese adults2. Flu virus spreads deeper in lungs of overweight, obese individuals3. Obese, overweight individuals more likely to spread virus4. Antibody response present, but T-cells not functioning VOICEOVER (in English): "According to NPR, scientists have found that the flu vaccine is less effective for people with excess weight.""A study from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill found that vaccinated obese adults have twice the risk of flu or flu-like illnesses compared to vaccinated healthy-weight adults.""NPR reports that during the 2009 flu outbreak, health experts noticed the infection was worse in individuals who were significantly overweight.""The virus grows to higher concentrations and spreads deeper in the lungs.""Heavier individuals were also more likely to spread the disease.""A University of Maryland study found that more of the virus came out of the exhaled breath of those who were overweight or obese. ""According to Chapel Hill nutrition professor Melinda Beck, the metabolic shift in people's bodies caused by gaining excess weight affects immune system cells.""So although obese people may still make an antibody response, their T-cells aren't functioning, so they can still be infected with the flu despite being vaccinated."SOURCES: NPR, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, University of Marylandhttps://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2019/11/24/782079520/excess-weight-can-weaken-the-flu-shothttps://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29161078https://www.pnas.org/content/115/5/1081 ***]]></description>
